			<h2 id="scroll_results">Understanding Your FollowBias</a></h2>
			<hr/>
      <p>On social media, each of us chooses exactly who we listen to for news, science, gossip, and casual conversation. These choices filter and bias the information we consume, even if it's unintentional. When we share or retweet content, we pass our FollowBias to our own networks.</p>
      <p>Taking control of our filters starts with awareness. FollowBias calculates the gender diversity of who you choose to follow. It accesses the public list of accounts you follow and estimates gender based on first name. You can return anytime to see how your FollowBias has changed; our server updates every six hours.</p>
      <p>FollowBias only collects public information that you reveal on your public Twitter profile. You can close your account anytime by following these <a href="https://support.twitter.com/articles/76052-connecting-or-revoking-third-party-applications">instructions on revoking third party access</a>. If you have any further questions about our use of public data, please <a href="#about">contact us</a>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="section"> 
      <h2>Why FollowBias?</h2>
       <hr/>
       <p>We, along with so many people we admire, care about including and listening to more women. We built FollowBias to understand and manage the impact of our filters on the content we create, consume and share.</p>
       <p>Gender bias is a sensitive subject, but it ought not be a shameful one. Who can claim that they can't do better? Our goal is to provide a tool to help individuals change their own behavior, not to shame or judge others. Given how wildly Twitter use varies a FollowBias score out of context is not a judgment of you as a person.</p>
       <p>Future versions of FollowBias will offer more metrics, recommendations, and the chance to compare yourself to peers. With your feedback and help, we can build a tool that supports diversity based on what works. Thanks for participating! <a href="https://github.com/c4fcm/fbserver/issues/new">Please add bug reports to Github</a>.</p>
       </p>
    </div>
  
  </div>

