 		  <h2 id="scroll_about">About FollowBias</h2>
      <p><a href="https://twitter.com/natematias">J. Nathan Matias</a> and <a href="https://twitter.com/dearsarah">Sarah Szalavitz</a> met at the MIT Media Lab in 2012 and discovered they shared some of the same crazy dreams about <a href="http://civic.mit.edu/blog/natematias/women-news-and-the-internet-almost-everything-we-know">measuring and changing</a> <a href="http://www.wired.co.uk/magazine/archive/2012/04/ideas-bank/sarah-szalavitz">gender diversity</a> in the media. A few months later, we managed to convince <a href="https://twitter.com/jameshome">James Home</a> to contribute to the project, who has made the project even more spectacular.</p>
      <p>J. Nathan Matias is a grad student at the MIT Media Lab Center for Civic Media, advised by <a href="https://twitter.com/ethanz">Ethan Zuckerman</a>. Nathan collaborates on technology and communities which empower people to become <a href="http://hypatia.media.mit.edu:3000/">more creative, effective, and informed</a>.</p>
      <p>Sarah Szalavitz is the CEO of 7Robot, a social design firm.  She also serves as a fellow at the MIT Media Lab, where she teaches <a href="http://web.media.mit.edu/~asetapen/MAS964/">Social Design</a>. Sarah is fascinated by the impossible, eager for more data, convinced by behavioral economics, and hopes to help people ask better questions.</p>
      <p>James Home is a product designer who works on mysterious things at Google.</p>
      <p>Email us at <strong><a href="mailto:followbias@gmail.com">followbias@gmail.com</a></strong> with questions about FollowBias, <a href="http://source.mozillaopennews.org/en-US/articles/under-hood-open-gender-tracker/">Open Gender Tracker</a>, Skirts on a Panel, and our other projects focused on gender diversity.</p>
      <hr/>
    </div>
